    "First, we introduce our notion of a solution to (1.1)-(1.5).",
    "Definition 2.1.",
    "A quadruple (µ, φ, ξ, σ) is called a solution to the initial-boundary value problem(1.1)-(1.5) if µ ∈ H 2 (0, T; V *) ∩ W 1,∞ (0, T; H) ∩ L ∞ (0, T; V), (2.7) φ ∈ W 1,∞ (0, T; H) ∩ H 1 (0, T; V) ∩ L ∞ (0, T; W) ∩ C 0 (Q), (2.8) σ ∈ H 1 (0, T; H) ∩ C 0 ([0, T]; V) ∩ L 2 (0, T; W), (2.9) ξ ∈ L ∞ (0, T; H),(2.10)and if (µ, φ, ξ, σ) satisfies⟨α∂ tt µ, v⟩ + Ω ∂ t φ v + Ω ∇µ • ∇v = Ω P (φ)(σ + χ (1 -φ) -µ)v - Ω h(φ)u 1 vfor every v ∈ V and a.e.",
    "in (0, T), (2.11)τ ∂ t φ -∆φ + ξ + F ′ 2 (φ) = µ + χ σ, ξ ∈ ∂F 1 (φ), a.e.",
    "in Q, (2.12) ∂ t σ -∆σ = -χ ∆φ -P (φ)(σ + χ (1 -φ) -µ) + u 2 a.e."
